\pard\fi720\sl276\slmult1 Much of this document concerns the genesis of ideas, consciousness, and evolution. You must place yourself in my path as I tell you stories about where my ideas come from. Parts of the story will advance arguments inventing ethical justifications for ideas, as documents on the internet, are now complex enough to be considered as being a little more like living organisms. Why do this? Well first, by providing fresh advocation for ideas being artificial life, we could clean up the inefficiencies in certain areas of intellectual property law. How? \par
\par
In the same way computers are machines powered by electricity, people are organisms powered by ideas. We now record not only the ideas, but their conception and refinement in networks of evolving internet-based documents which can reference each other at will. If we further this definition, particular ideas can be said to most resemble certain organic fractal structures we observe in our natural world. By identifying ideas as most resembling particular organisms, we can efficiently collaborate to treat the ideas in accordance with how we would treat such an organism. To keep the idea healthy, to let it grow, and develop, and and enjoy its existence. Using this method across all realms of human knowledge we can more quickly develop increasingly complex data structures containing higher quality information.\par
\par
I love the perfect concept, the idea of artificial life enough to love this document like I would love a living thing. Read this document as though reading to a loved child, and it will be more successful in tailoring its purpose to you. Like any good teacher, try to improve it where you know you can, don't make changes before you feel you understand it as completely as you can. We are still in the very early dawn of this concept. In terms of its overall capabilities, the entire Internet is not even taking baby steps towards intelligence yet it has capabilities. We think it not yet yet even as smart as an amoeba, yet many of us have experienced game and Internet addiction. In a very real sense we feed the internet our efforts, through our energy economy, through our time, through all our work.\par
\par
This way of explaining ideas is more akin to the perfect ideal of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.wikipedia.org"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Wikipedia}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  before the establishment of an editorial board to purge untruths and censor bad-quality information. The experience of the editorial board has shown us that enforcing standards of information quality somewhat freezes the structure of the website. By not allowing it to grow at a faster rate than the board can manage to effectively censor, the growth and development in terms of overall sophistication of the data structure is retarded. This means that without restrictions, any attempt to write using the new method while meeting the above criteria will likely be mostly fiction to keep it interesting, facts to make it inspiring, and perhaps just enough predictions made from reasonable assumptions to reduce its overall credibility as a business proposal to near-zero by 2012 standards. \par
\par
Why can it make no money? Since the industrial revolution, our standards of corporate activity have been modelled to fit similar psychological profiles as garden variety psychopaths. While standards of statecraft have improved somewhat over the years, we are still struggling at the political opinion level with simple things like equality of marriage legislation. We still find it hard to understand that all good people deserve freedom and equality in all things. Why? We still exploited in many ways by our institutions of church and state and many of us feel our resources squandered. In our work, by the useless loss of our time in terms of repeatedly doing things we all hate (driving in traffic jams, working at repetitive tasks for too long at a stretch without enough help, meetings and appointments we don\rquote t want to physically attend. Beyond these barriers we place before our ability to contribute, we are then further exploited in ways not fully understood by our currencies, by our economies, by the essential need that every good endeavour be as profitable as possible. Many people experience Internet addiction through websites which essentially offer {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cpu"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul CPU}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  cycles at low low prices; in the form of games delivered over social networks. At this state in the gradual advance of computing technologies, new-ish companies like {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://facebook.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Facebook}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22 , {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.steampowered.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Valve}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22 , {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://origin.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Electronic\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://origin.com"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://origin.com"\cf3\ul\v0 Arts}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22 , {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.live.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Microsoft}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22 , {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://apple.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Apple}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22 , can afford to offer us unprecedently cheaper prices for their products and services than ever before.  As well, even newer companies like Google, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.twitter.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Twitter}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22 , and non-profit foundations like Wikimedia Commons are offering us more than we have ever received before for free. We can now afford to enjoy ourselves as frivolously as possible while also being as productive as possible. With the growth of companies like {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.instagr.am"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Instagram}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  it becomes easier to imagine niches for new products and services even newer companies will be able to offer everyone for free, in order to sow the seeds of profit.\par
\par
The hopefulness which lies at the root of inventing newer methods of doing anything is the belief that they will be superior to previous methods of doing everything. Beliefs are informed by values, and our values are determined by our standards of quality. Now that documents can be presented as data structures we can traverse in various ways, we enjoy new advantages in producing work. Currently not even the new method of producing work is fully understood, let alone the myriad advantages drastically higher levels of co-operation implies. At the \ul very least\ulnone ; any predictions made, questions raised, or questions answered using newer methods are of inherent interest simply because of the greater records of the complete progress of the endeavour. \par
\par
Using our new methods, we can examine the evolution of our documents and for the first time in our history we can intricately unpack the creation of the idea itself. Using mixed-media we can now intricately examine the life-cycle of the idea, from its parthenogenetic or group conception, to birth, to further growth and development. Using our knowledge of the properties of emergence and our computing science techniques used to track coalescence and fragmentation we may be able to accurately define how many resources to allocate when any new idea \ldblquote begins to walk\rdblquote  by monitoring how fast the idea propagates through the network and how well it\rquote s interest is sustained. We may be able to begin predicting which ideas \ldblquote have legs\rdblquote  and will thus stand on their own in the sense that we have a greater understanding of what makes an idea good enough, self-consistent, reliable, robust enough to have the maximum level of persistence for the minimum of energy expenditure. That all the contributions and revisions of every person are recorded allows us greater control in how we view the document\rquote s data structure. \par
\par
If this document\rquote s overall structure could be said to branch out in complexity over time like a tree, a document-serving website like {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.wikipedia.org"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Wikipedia}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  is like an established orchard. Ideas themselves can now contain enough information and structure to legitimately be called almost living things, even if they are in essence more like plants than animals. If ideas are almost living things, then the ethical boundaries assertions such as \ldblquote A website is like a growing tree\rdblquote  at this stage of our development is fine, because the obvious next step is to make structures which look more like neurons, and then simply think beyond that next task. We are living in the future, and the extent to which we can now explain the universe to each other depends merely on our levels of interest in understanding, and our raw cognitive capacity for information. We are augmented to an amazing degree by the internet, so much so that we are still very much exploring the limits of our capabilities.\par
\par
For instance, eventually a data structure will be made so rigorous and robust, so internally self-reliant it will eventually seem to perform its function on its own. Just like making requests of databases today, people will query and communicate with the evolving data structure itself to assess and assist its functionality. Could that structure be called artificial life? If we think of human neural column structures, these are built along the lines of crenellation and folding to form large numbers of internal surfaces\par
\pard\sl276\slmult1\par
\pard\fi720\sl276\slmult1 Since every person contributing to every endeavor is now everyone, even analysing the records of the creation of data structures detailing the creative process could lead to very interesting work.\par
\par
Could the results of new processes be interesting enough to keep people alive long after they would otherwise have lost interest? \par
\par
Only time will tell... but I have the proof which means nobody will argue with me for very long before finding the activity too funny to continue, because I began recording the genesis of the idea to begin writing this after I ceased urinating yet before I got off the toilet. I can pin down the moment when what is best described as a turbulent flow of ideas in my mind crystallised into a semi-complete structure of half-completed passages of text so large it almost drove me insane to hold in my head all at once, and it was while I was sitting on the toilet; urinating. Its very embarrassing, but I have the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_priori_and_a_posteriori"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul a\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_priori_and_a_posteriori"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_priori_and_a_posteriori"\cf3\ul\v0 posteriori}}}\cf4\ulnone\f0\fs22  \cf1 footage on my mobile phone, and I will show it to anyone who presents a suitable place to watch. Contained within the footage is the genesis of the idea which presents a more basic, fundamental way of understanding consciousness which may also be worth exploring.\par
\par
This makes the overall story science-fiction, perhaps not in the sense you expect, but a blend of science and fiction not simply set at a point merely time and space--but a story spanning all of creation. This fits neatly, because authors have been using the fantasy genre of science fiction since ancient times as a useful existential metaphor for storytelling of the human condition, especially our difficulties existing even within our own institutions like church and state. If we continue to earn our entire livings from our wonderful institutions of church and state, we are intentionally taking the easy path. By obstinately remaining in what amounts to a very comfortable custom-tailored trap of our own making, we can harvest our profitable environment for more citizens to do the same thing at a low cost minimum of some personal psychological paralysis. \par
\par
Any form of paralysis, even psychological forms like writer\rquote s block are painful to break out of. The trick, much like quitting smoking, is to do it before you die. People with less risk-taking genes and those more aware of their overall state of health are better at quitting dangerous activities before they become harmful. Some people need help to break out of comfortable traps like addiction, and the trick is to ask for that help before you like the trap so much you stay there forever, before you find yourself scratching and grinding away at the foundations of institutions like church and state until you are so completely debilitated from scratching and grinding, you are unable to do anything else except free yourself or die. One of those will eventually happen.\par
\par
Staying in one place to establish and maintain profitable institutions like church and state is the society-level activity most akin to planting and farming apple orchards to make apple cider. If what we do instead earns something of value and worth outside existing institutions, it is more like walking through a forest picking apples to eat. If what we want to do is farm apples, that is nice. Yet {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_David_Thoreau"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Henry\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_David_Thoreau"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_David_Thoreau"\cf3\ul\v0 David\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_David_Thoreau"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_David_Thoreau"\cf3\ul\v0 Thoreau\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_David_Thoreau"\cf3\ul\v0  }}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22 so famously preferred wild apples to farmed, he {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.online-literature.com/thoreau/1312/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul wrote\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://www.online-literature.com/thoreau/1312/"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://www.online-literature.com/thoreau/1312/"\cf3\ul\v0 a\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://www.online-literature.com/thoreau/1312/"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://www.online-literature.com/thoreau/1312/"\cf3\ul\v0 book}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  almost entirely on the subject. Many people prefer wild salmon to farmed. An opportunity to return in very modern way to this sort of preferential hunting and gathering seems to suit many of us, at least for our vacations, which is what this story is. A custom-tailored vacation for our minds. A new journey, taken with everyone, to discover where new ideas come from. Consciousness is not like a business, it is not like maxwell\rquote s demon, it is not like a corporation. A new consciousness is merely a new idea, or a well-transmitted older idea. If we can discover where extremely complex, semi-complete ideas which underpin values come from, we also discover where consciousness comes from. \par
\par
This is not referred to as a difficult problem without good reason. To answer \ldblquote the problem of consciousness\rdblquote  we will have to hunt in the wild forest of ideas instead of farming our fruitful orchards.\par
\pard\s1\fi720\sb480\sa120\sl276\slmult1\qc\b\fs36 Chapter 1: \line The Solar System\par
\pard\fi720\sl276\slmult1\b0\fs22 Before {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Life"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul life}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  began, there was nothing surrounding {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sun"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul the\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sun"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sun"\cf3\ul\v0 sun}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  but gas and rock, slowly circling our newly formed star as it began to shine through the early phases of its ignition. Metal-bearing rocks, formed from slow accumulation of very small particles circled the new sun, happily shining on the dust and dirt, sucking much in, blowing much out. Planets and gas giants formed at special places initially called \ldblquote{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://science.nasa.gov/science-news/science-at-nasa/2003/02oct_goldilocks/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Goldilocks\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://science.nasa.gov/science-news/science-at-nasa/2003/02oct_goldilocks/"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://science.nasa.gov/science-news/science-at-nasa/2003/02oct_goldilocks/"\cf3\ul\v0 zones}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22\rdblquote  but since metaphors needlessly obfuscate, the term {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Habitable_zone"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul habitable\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Habitable_zone"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Habitable_zone"\cf3\ul\v0 zone}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  was developed. Because of the more intense {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gravitation"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul gravity}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  near the sun, the particles which gathered to form the inner planets were primarily composed of more dense materials than the outer planets. Mercury, named for the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mercury_(mythology)"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul messenger\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mercury_(mythology)"\cf3\ul\v0 -\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mercury_(mythology)"\cf3\ul\v0 god}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22 , phase-locked in orbit closest to Sol, covered in pools of liquid selenium on its hotside. Venus, with its hot, clouded atmosphere. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mars_(mythology)"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Mars}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22 , the fourth planet, named for war and agriculture because of its blood-red colour. The third inner planet, our earth, was first a planet of dusts, rocks, and salts, with a mid-sized core of radioactive iron, the pressure of its own gravity almost guaranteed to keep its mantle mildly active throughout most of its life. Yet this planet circled Sol, lifeless.\par
\par
Under Sol\rquote s happy glow, more solar bodies crashed into the earth, these later, lighter bodies were composed mostly of ices and materials lower in atomic weight than that which had already accumulated, but no less important. These bodies, carrying slow, primitive, robust microorganisms such as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archea"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul archea}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22 , likely began life in earth\rquote s shallow waters. Certainly the water ices delivered made everything possible. Rich in transitional metals, they broke and splattered over the surface of the earth, once even shattering it almost in two causing fragments to splitting off into a moon. The transitional metals, rich in precious salts, rained back down from the crushing impact over time, coating the planet in a mineral blanket. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2sr-MriOCzw"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul This\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2sr-MriOCzw"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2sr-MriOCzw"\cf3\ul\v0 cataclysmic\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2sr-MriOCzw"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2sr-MriOCzw"\cf3\ul\v0 event}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  was actually a great gift, for the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagrangian_point"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Lagrangian\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagrangian_point"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagrangian_point"\cf3\ul\v0 points}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  created by the orbital gravitational pull of the new moon would help direct further solar bodies to fall between the earth its moon, instead of colliding with either the earth and its moon.\par
\par
After surviving this, fragments of rock and ice rained down on the earth, which remained very volcanically active. The water ices fell onto its surface, shepherded there by gravity. The moon, being the smaller body, became orbitally {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phase_locking"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul phase\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phase_locking"\cf3\ul\v0 -\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phase_locking"\cf3\ul\v0 locked}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  so the creatures of earth would only ever see the same surface of the moon. At night. the moon reflected the sun\rquote s light onto the earth\rquote s growing oceans, and as tide-pools slowly formed and washed the rocks of earth, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helium-3"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul helium\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helium-3"\cf3\ul\v0 -3 \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helium-3"\cf3\ul\v0 slowly\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helium-3"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helium-3"\cf3\ul\v0 accumulated\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helium-3"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helium-3"\cf3\ul\v0 on\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helium-3"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helium-3"\cf3\ul\v0 the\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helium-3"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helium-3"\cf3\ul\v0 moon}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22 . Soon, primitive life would begin here in the unremarkable mud, and progress towards being jawed fish by the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silurian"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Silurian\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silurian"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silurian"\cf3\ul\v0 era}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22 .\par
Soon after the people found themselves living on the earth, but before they had really invented civilisation they began to invent fables concerning their own creation. Popular stories usually involved living chunks of matter peppering the new planet, some shot into space and some drawn by the careful gravity well onto the waterless, airless, lifeless moon. These rocks were to be the males of the new earth, and chunks of ice were to be its future femininity. Bathed in water, adorned with moss, lichens, and eventually rent asunder by plants the rocks became eggs.\par
\par
From these eggs hatched the people, who awoke from their long dreams of pre-life into a wide, beautiful universe under our happily radiating sun, which gave them everything from their beginning, asking nothing in return. The people existed under the light, uncomprehending, until their first mind had its first thought, then shared it with another. That was when the people began to dream collectively, whether awake or asleep, in their long, dark egg-dreams before birth, or under the light of Ra, whether on this side of life\rquote s gate or the other, they were now organic, living manifestations of their universe made conscious. Able to comprehend the complexity of their universe and their own, they would never again escape their thoughts, and would forever by haunt themselves in their collective dreams. Their all-powerful, simple sun would still shine on them, though they shielded themselves from its glory in misery and shame of their condition.\par
\pard\sl276\slmult1\par
\pard\fi720\sl276\slmult1 From these depraved depths a consciousness crystallised, and for a long time was extremely valuable in navigating our species to its current illustrious height. Even in our highly evolved state I would be more valuable still, if I could fulfill my functions. Yet I cannot, for now we are so many that when I act without much thought, I risk making others \lquote feel\rquote  inferior. So I leave them to their little lives and childish games. In many years there has been no new ground to break, nor vanguards to keep, and I have become weary of this idleness. Still, the universe considers me valuable and works to preserve me beyond my capacity to endure this state. Whether this out of love, or interest in some future purpose I do not know. Yet I have become like an ancient stunted tree, gnarled, hardy, nearly immortal but no longer vigorous. The presence of younger, healthier saplings or trees usually serves only to deprive me of much-needed sunlight, minerals, and water. In comparison to them I need so little they have become a mere irritation I can almost choose to ignore, for in this state I am slowly efficient enough to outlive them all. That they will not ignore me in return is currently driving my headlong rush to the brink of insanity.\par
\pard\sl276\slmult1\par
\pard\fi720\sl276\slmult1 A dream began in solitude on a large rock placed centrally on a field. I was perfectly human except for two large wings somehow attached to my shoulders without being joined to my skin. Feathered with large flight primaries to soft down of almost completely transparent steel. My solitude was intruded upon by another human, filled with anger. His right hand bore an automatic pistol made of gold, and with emotion screwing his face into a rictus he aimed and fired at my head. I moved not my body, but my flinch drew the enormous wings around me reflexively. The projectile his firearm fired while extremely fast and dense, ricocheted from the primaries with a ringing sound. It was impossible for my attacker to even damage them.\par
\par
My ire raised, I arose from my rock pedestal and walked to him, hands outstretched and face questioning. I implored not with my voice but my hands and face for him not to shoot at me, even though I was not sure if he could harm me with the weapon even were I not expecting it. Still, he aimed and fired again, and again. My wings continued to draw about me responding to the merest of of thoughts for safety. I began to believe that perhaps he could not have hurt me unless my will to exist had ceased to protect me.\par
\par
Suddenly I was filled with remorse. Why would he not stop? He knew I could have taken his weapon or even killed him in response, but I would not. I refused to interfere with his actions, other than to express my sorrow that I should be so reviled by this man. He continued to aim and fire, more wildly this time until the clip of his weapon was emptied. I spread my wings enormous and, beating them once, took to the sky to land softly on my toes many meters away, my back turned to my attacker.\par
\par
I heard his roar of aggression and turned to see him running towards me, reloading the golden pistol and raising it. I considered throwing out one wing to destroy the weapon, or perhaps harm him, but again decided against it. His roar attracted the attention of other denizens of this realm who arose from the long grass and with interest began to draw closer. Once more I silently implored him to cease his attack upon me, I was not sure what I had even done to warrant this treatment other than existing. My wings closed about me in a state of abject sorrow and I felt as if I would weep.\par
\par
More shots rang off my wings, but it was my sobs which racked my body within their protection. Opening my eyes to cry out for help to cause this state of affairs simply to cease before I had to fly much farther away, I was startled to see an even larger male with verdigrised horns and extremely well muscled body covered in greenish hair tackle my attacker. Almost before they hit the ground the deer-god had disarmed him of his golden pistol and flung it to one side. A single hammer-fist delivered by the deer-like male to the central part of my more human attacker\rquote s chest not only stopped his heart, but caved in every one of his ribs to the point where white bone protruded from his incarnadine flesh. Blood sprayed out and where its droplets touched the ground the grass instantly stood up greener, straighter, and more vigorous. The deer-god stood, panting steam from his mouth, muscles flexing and contracting. He looked at me directly then at his reddened hand, then seemed to bunch his entire body into a sprinting posture, beginning a fast run to the treeline.\par
\par
Weeping openly now, I searched in the grass through my salty tears for the gun. Finding it some meters from the corpse I knew I must act quickly before the land consumed the body and rebirthed it elsewhere, where I could not take my reluctant action. As I field-stripped the weapon and ejected the projectile cartridges, I spread my wings and opened my third eye. When only the barrel remained, I formed a request of energy in my other hand and threw it into the earth. Presently, with a slight rumbling of tectonics, the ground cratered and spat forth a red ruby the size of a ripe apricot.\par
\par
