\pard\fi720\sl276\slmult1 Even in such a dreamscape nobody can sit upon their rock forever, no matter how high atop the mountain peak it lies. Returning to the flatland and folding my wings about myself small enough to be nearly invisible, I went to a university campus near the beach. in the courtyard I watched the news on the distractingly-placed television, waiting to place an order for food at the campus cafe. I wasn't sure I was going to meet Satan then, nor that he was my uncle, or that I had met him before. I was at the university I attended unsatisfactorily, and had just come from an appointment during which I'd asked whether the Dean of Admissions had ever heard of another campus near a small township nearby. He hadn't heard of such a place, and even though I had striking memories of spending almost a year in its ivy-covered halls, listening to ivy-covered professors rattle on about, of all things, chemistry. I took a walk outside to clear my head and found myself watching a television tuned to a commercial news network. The reporter mentioned that there had been a spate of financial frauds on the Gold Coast, involving a strange kind of brothel there. As the article progressed it showed a woman with what could have been the softest breasts in the world, topped with the largest, sweetest nipples in creation (we're talking juicy teats the size of small apricots adorning Josephine-style champagne-glass sized handfuls of sweater meat). The breasts on the TV were almost on full display and I think what helped them make it past the censor was the fact that they were unapologetically completely tattooed in the Indian style with geometric designs in the most lovely colours of the rainbow. Her nipples were almost iridescent with colour, going from deep purple at the tips to a dull reddish tinge covering the aureaola, her breasts and most of her decollette stippled in teardop shapes in these and other complementary shades.\par
\par
With my head struggling with colour theory and thoughts about the properties of subcutaneous collagen I watched the rest of the article in a daze, unable to tear myself away while the reporter spoke of the fraudulent transactions which had been made by a customer of the brothel, which was not so much a brothel as a new-age retreat for the sexually inept, providing services along the lines of many BD/SM social groups but for money. The twist provided was that the inmates (I call them that because it was not immediately obvious whether they were there of their own free will or not, mostly because it was obfuscated as to whether they possessed free will at all, given the state they were kept in) were mostly zentai-clad submissives acting out the roles of animals to please clients. Sucked through the television to the actual place, I lay on the floor although I had been in a standing position next to the madame; the only one showing her human face and recognisably human even though her peacock feathers rustled and unfurled most convincingly. Asking about the animatronics which made this possible I recieved a noncommittal response that she did not know how these things worked and chose not to inquire further into the matter.\par
\par
I watched with increasing unease as she put her charges through their paces, a radio in the background continued to recite information about the fraudulent transactions. Several girls and one boy half-cavorted, half-crawled around the hardwood gym floor imitating to great effect the animals their costumes made of them, much to my disgust. The nugget of information I had waited for clued me in to what was going on when the announcer said that transactions had been made from the brothel's numbered account which allowed both deposits and withdrawals. Oddly, I knew the client who had somehow gotten hold of the appropriate numbers and made over 1000 withdrawals from the account, nearly leaving the place insolvent and in danger of closing. The madame continued to extoll the manifold physical virtues of her charges and made increasingly desperate entreaties that I should purchase time with at least one of my choosing, knowing I was aware of the dire financial situation. I'd sooner have strangled her and sent all these spandex'ed, mindwiped, pitiful things free into the outside world to rediscover their humanity underneath a glaring sun. I didn't tell her that, instead I mentioned that I'd been listening to the news and may have known how the withdrawals happened. I thought it was was my uncle's son, and that I should probably tell my uncle. She told me I could bear that kind of message all by myself.\par
\par
She followed me to the door I intended to leave via to some form of transport, I think the only reason she let me go rather than pull on my arm to stay was that, and of this I was again uneasily certain, my 'uncle' (who was never really my uncle but rather a disreputable friend of my father's, a man who used to show up drunk on my birthday during childhood and say things like "What a beautiful child! I'm going to throw it up in the air!" and otherwise worry attending adults). The man in question happened to be almost outside the door.\par
"Uncle! Have you heard the news about this place?" I offered by way of greeting.\par
"Is that why you're here?" he effusively responded, offering me a grin which split his face rather pleasantly. He was never much to look at, but I didn't mind his bent nose, his shifty eyes, alcohol-sodden breath, or chameleonic manner. To me his was just the way of the sort who used to throw my childhood form high into the air on birthdays, to my unaccountable delight and the boundless worries of my family.\par
\par
I saw I didn't need to tell him who I thought may have caused the ruin of the establishment, the things which were burgeoning on the edges of my awareness suddenly fell into place. There was no university of Buderim on the range hinterlands yet, the time I spent there had all been a dream. He defintely owned the Gold Coast brothel I had been sucked though the television on the Sunshine Coast into, and probably kept close tabs on his own son, and maybe even knew more about his motivations for bleeding the place dry through the magic of anonymous banking than I could deduce from haphazard attention to the news media. I decided to respond slightly more carefully.\par
"Well, I suppose I'm here because I heard about it, but I think perhaps all I can offer are my condolences for such misfortune." I left out that I had been drawn here through some kind of attention-driven teleportation as I was sure the response I would recieve is that he simply didn't concern himself with such technology.\par
"Perhaps you'd just like to visit?" he exclaimed, turning his face-splitting grin into a mere wry smile. He quickly crossed the room and opened the door onto a loading dock. The brothel inmates shied from the light, while their madam shielded them an ostentatious display of decidedly organimatronic feathers, while the radio mentioned that investigations were continuing into gaining an interview with the family of the man now known to own the establishment. The investigative reporters had hit a roadblock in that they could not find his address. Just a mailbox on the side of the road with no house behind it.\par
Seeing my attention split between his holding the door to the loading dock open and the radio he added "You know how I like my privacy. I keep the place hidden like it always was." Indeed I knew, I had an intense feeling of deja-vu at this juncture, as memories long suppressed fell into place unbidden.\par
"Shall we go? Have you changed anything?" I asked, galvanised to action and again moving my limbs to propel me through the door.\par
"Not as much as you've changed things, my girl." was his quick response while he lay a hand on my shoulder. His palm was hot, but not very sweaty.\par
"That wasn't really a change of anything so much as mind, uncle. I'm pretty close to that particular flux point I think." referring to my gender.\par
"True, truth at that. Still, I like what you've done, you know. Couldn't have predicted it, I think." he rambled almost to himself, initiating a rolling gait over to a scissor lift he operated with dexterity to travel to the floor of the dock. I stood on the lift, but declined to operate the controls myself. He smiled at me again and brought me down, joltingly and without skill. I didn't so much as stumble or grip a handrail, perferring I guess to show my skill at remaining upright by keeping my hands free at my sides. The unease had returned mostly to the pit of my stomache.\par
"You know how I like most of all to keep the entrance hidden." he said while keying a security code on a nondescript panel. The loading dock's garage door began rolling up, and a hidden personal access panel popped open in the very wall. He slipped through the hidden panel with inhuman speed and I caught sight of him a moment later, actually rolling like a ball to where the door was just opening to adult height. He stood up and I decided to mention the physical changes I'd noticed in him as well.\par
"Its nice to see you've lost weight, uncle." The last time I'd seen him he'd been drinking far too much, and his health was suffering. His paunch was gone, and apparently with its loss her had rediscovered the physical prowess he'd possessed in no small manner during the years of my childhood.\par
"Thanks! Its nice to see someone notices. I just wish your aunt would!"\par
"Give it time, she's bound to see eventually." at this, he looked at me sidelong, not as a child who was simply too clever by half but as if I'd said something profound. I didn't smile back.\par
"There's one thing that's still the same, you know."\par
"Ah, I was wondering if we'd do that again." we walked into a different room encircled by a metal rails painted safety yellow. From the floor sprang on hydraulic robot arms a half-dozen panels of wood, each about an inch thick and about one meter square, arrayed in a sort of obstacle course out of a dimly-remembered but often played puzzle platforming game. My uncle walked about the edge of the room behind the safety rail and motioned that I should begin on the first panel.\par
"The last time I was here these panels were made of thin, hard metal." I remembered aloud as I alighted to the first one. It shuddered under my feet and attempted to throw me off, so I jumped and pirouetted to the next.\par
"They still move the same, though. Oh nice one!" he exclaimed as I went from panel to panel, performing flips, handstands, and any number of gymnastic feats designed to prove that such a challenge as this was mere child's play to my mind's the adult housing of body. The last wooden panel was twice as large as the others, one could lie down on it. There were hydraulic rams placed around it though, all tipped with smaller bits of 1" thick wood, its obvious purpose was to enclose and perhaps squash anyone foolish enough to land in such an inviting trap, and indeed my uncle's hand was poised over a button to operate his impromptu coffin. I pretended to slip upon landing, altering my centre of gravity as much as I could to make it look accidental by allowing my feet to slip out from under me and falling, spinning. My hands grabbed the yellow safety rail securely.\par
"That counts, doesn't it? My feet are still touching the end panel."\par
"That they are, that they are." he said, repeating himself awkwardly like a child who has been discovered when about to pull a particularly irritating plank. "Wouldn't have hurt you though."\par
"Last time, I remember it did. It doesn't damage me, but avoiding needless pain is something I've learned to do for my own reasons." while I said this, I displayed my strength by pulling myself rather slowly into a handstand on the safety rail, then folding my body around and down onto the gangway.\par
He turned from watching me move my body through his obstacle course abruptly and went to another door. This one opened into a deserted changing changing rooms of a swimming pool. I followed his quick pace past the showers and out to the Olympic-sized, 8-lane, fully enclosed competition area currently in use for training. A man in a red shirt lettered "INSTRUCTOR" in white quickly approached my uncle, imparting that although training began soon they would be willing to postpone until such time as he no longer had need of the place while I looked around in recollection.\par
The last time I was here I remembered the pool had been drained after such an exchange while I watched. My uncle's study was literally beneath the pool through a well-concealed trapdoor. A room encircled with animal heads on plaques, a fireplace to one side of an enormous desk with quill pens and ink pots, a gun safe, and two sturdy leatherbound armchairs atop a rug made of polar bear skin with the head still attached. I half-recalled a dog asleep in one corner, or perhaps three dogs, although I couldn't quite make out there being enough tails or legs. I shook my head to clear the memories, and thought that it was fitting that I should not have to invade his more private sanctum during this visitation. I knew there was something he would rather show me much more, even though I had already seen previously.\par
After explaining we wouldn't need to interrupt the training session, my uncle asked me to follow him, there was something he wanted me to see.\par
"Do you mean someone? Is it her?" I asked, pre-empting any further banter.\par
"Yes, her. She's as lovely as ever." he admitted.\par
"Ever as lovely, I know." I responded. He led me down a small corridor, into what could probably be described as a grotto. set into the wall near the ceiling of this room was a grille of iron bars, through which by standing on tiptoe we could view a woman and another red-shirted man lettered "INSTRUCTOR" in white handling a turtle out of a tank. Peering around the turtle we could see they were displaying it to a small crowd of schoolchildren, wide-eyed with wonder at this marine reptile.\par
"You can see she's been injured out in the open ocean, perhaps she was hit by the prow of a boat or the screw of a propellor and that impact has cracked her shell through to her tail." the woman spoke in an excellent teaching voice, almost as if she were narrating a wildlife program in front of her little attentive class "Out there, she would have died or been eaten by sharks but here we're attempting to repair her shell using the same material as a dentist uses to fill holes in human teeth. You can see here where it looks like someone has drawn on her back with a white marker? Thats where the filling has gone. We had to take her out of the water and sedate her to perform the operation but the broken segments of her shell will be completely healed in a matter of months, then we can release her." this statement was followed by admiring, appreciative gasps of amazement from the schoolchildren aged five to seven. Their little faces moved in to examine the turtle and little lips moved to ask their questions of the woman. My uncle and I watched and listened to this marine biology lesson in a moment of shared happiness; me because of the teaching and learning I was witness to and him because he could view my aunt. I wondered why he just watched this way, but I supposed it was because their relationship was more complex than I had experience with, to the point where perhaps only this concealed viewing of her life was possible for him. Looking upon his enraptured face staring at her at that moment I felt some small pity for their situation.\par
"But when turtles hide from sharks, do their spines fold up?" the questioning from one small child had progressed into another area altogether unconcerned with artificial shell composites.\par
"Well, their spines are very different from ours, and from x-ray video we can see thats not only what happens. Their spinal discs compress and also fold in several places, around the neck, fins, and tail there are special compartments which accept and hold the new position of the bones..." I let myself fall down from the small grille back onto my heels, not waiting nor willing to learn much more about turtles in this uncomfortable position.\par
"Well, she never changes, always showing those kids that marine life of hers." he offered.\par
"Naturally." I responded laconically.\par
"She's a goddess, not like us at all! We can only aspire." this was delivered in a pleading tone.\par
"Not so. We are as like unto gods as it is possible to be."\par
"Really now?"\par
"Yes, really. I'm not who that came from either. That was written by a Chinese philosopher named Lao Tzu, over three thousand years ago."\par
"Sounds interestingly deep. Almost like poetry" he raised his hand to his chin in consideration of Tzu's words.\par
"I think perhaps in that time, such a statement would have constituted a decent poem." I could see that much like the way he refused to consider the inner workings of his machinery, he had little conscious comprehension of the state of humanity during that period of our history. I got the impression that although he could have lived through it, being far older than I, his conscious rejection of ways to mark indelibly the passage of time rendered him incapable of remembering.\par
"Well, we'd better talk about why you're here." he grudgingly spoke. The words came out like hard-edged rocks.\par
"I followed you, I was concerned I think, when I saw the news at the university."\par
"Why didn't you finish what you were doing there?" his eyes flashed alarmingly and his right hand snaked out to grab my left arm above the elbow in a painful vise grip.\par
"I wasn't sure what exactly it I was doing. That other place you sent me to anyway didn't really exist, at least, not yet I think. Its hard to say why I wasn't sure but thats the reason." I displayed my palms in supplication, though it hurt my left bicep.\par
"What about the deep stuff though? You could be the one to tackle the amazing things, like; Thou shalt not hurt!" Leaving aside the thought that this wasn't even one of the ten Christian commandments at all, I took the obvious objection which sprang readily to mind from my knowledge of medical science.\par
"But all of those receptors are known, and have been bound with various chemicals! There's nothing new to be done there!" I thrashed painfully in his tight grip on my left elbow, knowing that soon I would have to wake to escape his increasingly mercurial presence. He screamed almost incoherently in my ear, his hair exploding into fire and his eyes going from red embers to blazingly white-hot. The breath of his scream burned on my skin and I knew I needed to go immediately. I tore myself from him, back to my new rock perch near the mountain\rquote s peak. I was suddenly cold. The chirping of a cricket and lack of light indicated it would be some hours until dawn.\par
