If you write a book titled \ldblquote How to Earn Lots Of Money Without Effort\rdblquote  it may get more than its fair share of interest. People would buy it, hoping to discover the scam. Presumably, these are the same people who ask questions such as \ldblquote Why are we spending so much money on science when people are starving?\rdblquote  It is very difficult to write a book which earns nothing, because it is very difficult to tell even one story absolutely \ul nobody\ulnone  is interested in. Writing a book which people are interested in, and which earns nothing, is more challenging. If you write a book which changes society but makes no money, are people really far less interested? People are interested in things which earn currency because these things are inherently interesting. But too many people go about the activity of \ldblquote earning a living\rdblquote  in what is in too much of our society considered drudgery. The essential problem is that earning money has become too typically linked with boring difficult activities. Taking the electricity energy economy as an example it is easy to extrapolate how our future problems disposing of all possible energy-bearing products will easily overshadow any we currently experience earning a living today. What will the world be like when our concept of money is more directly linked to energy than to a unit of agreed-upon value?\par
