\pard\s1\sb480\sa120\sl276\slmult1\qc\b\fs36 Chapter 4:\par
History, Time, Space, & Matter\par
\pard\fi720\sl276\slmult1\b0\fs22\par
If you write something which stays in print as long as possible it has to be so useful it continues cropping up. Since we evolved from our more natural hominid past we have discovered examples of primitive technologies which emerge from civilisation\rquote s prehistory. For as long as people have used snowshoes, finding fossil coelacanths, using obsidian blades, using fire to cook, make pottery, make rock hand axes, practicing metallurgy and medicine. Since before we were aware we could transmit ideas using language we have been using these technologies co-operatively as community groups. Your idea will have to remain useful enough to be recorded at least as long as these technologies have been passed on through the generations, so it will need to develop an impact similar to that which drives us to discover from the moment of consciousness onwards.\par
\par
In addition to this new way of producing work worth recording, I want to try a new way of living. From now on, I will accept reasonable suggestions on what to do from everyone. I will attempt to cultivate complete personal integrity in myself so I can be like ideal vision for this document. Open, transparent, and verifiable. With this integrity and I will be able to make reasonable suggestions to others. Albert Einstein is quoted as saying \ldblquote Only the life lived for others is worthwhile.\rdblquote  If at this point you are interested I ask to you to share this document with friends you believe may also be. It is publicly editable and I urge you to make any changes.\par
\par
Why? Because making people happy by changing their outlooks is inherently fun, interesting, profitable, and desirable just of itself. People don\rquote t willingly change, for example I\rquote ll continue repeating things as long as they remain true, like how people don\rquote t willingly change. People will most readily change by being forced to. \par
\par
This is a new way of producing high-quality work. Internet-assisted global collaboration works for many things already. Mathematical proofs, music (a choir as big as the Internet),to Catcerto. , Books can be written collaboratively too and this is an attempt to do so, and I am attempting to extend the collaborative working concept from authorship, to artistic works, to a collaborative way of living life.\par
\par
Unless an idea deals with thinking on the timescales of institutions like church and state, any ideas you have have will not make such an impact. Which is not to say they may not be recorded, but history thwarts less vigorous efforts to leave records.\par
\par
Evolving documents have always been efficient at replicating ideas. A good evolving document in the modern sense is even more memetic because it stores all revisions. It is open, creatively commons licensed, globally readable, and editable by anyone. It is open, organisationally transparent, and verifiable. It is linked to real people who strive to improve its quality. Any sufficiently good quality website, hosting high-quality subject matter will form a modern network of interlinked institutions to sustain itself. Institutions like the Wikipedia foundation and Wikimedia Commons are examples of such human institutions. The quality of the information provided by these institutions will always be equal to the standards and integrity of its editors, in these cases members of their editorial boards.\par
\par
This model can be improved by simply storing all revisions, rather than opaquely editing for only \lquote good quality\rquote  material. Even the pranks, vandalisms, and attempts at subversion must be recorded openly, transparently, and verifiably, then voted up or down in standards of quality by the community at large. Articles must be written, debunked, reproven. Never deleted, removed, or the publicly viewable edition modified . \par
\par
If your book is in print and not widely represented on the internet,especially at this point in history, it seems as if it may be less widely read in future years. It makes more money to have books in print, but its friendlier, and better available online.\par
\par
Everyone deserves the opportunity to be welcomed to life as a intelligently reasoning person. Every journey worth taking deserves a knowledgeable guide and telling stories is a guidance I have prepared for you to understand the world around us, and something of yourself, with all my love. Don\rquote t forget to breathe. Properly, and as much as possible.\par
\par
Don\rquote t stare at the sun. Bad things will happen. Also don\rquote t look into mirrors for too long, mirrors are mildly evil because they exploit a little-known image-reversing property of binocular vision which happens to only show you what you \b think\b0  you look like when you look at your own reflection. This happens because mirrors reverse the image you are seeing. Knowing this about  mirrors, you now know what you see when you look into the mirror less resembles you than what other people see when they look at you, or what you see when you look at a photograph of yourself--especially a photograph someone else has taken. Other people always seem to \ldblquote bring out our best side\rdblquote  which is an important skill when doing portrait photography. Doing anything which prevents you from absorbing information from and contributing to the sum of recorded knowledge may turn out to be a distraction, and photography is an inspiring art which is inherently interesting of itself because the attempt to record visuals of moments in time has greatly assisted in retaining knowledge and adding the sum of what is recorded.\par
\par
We all possess our minds, bodies, and pluck. We are mostly fluids, and even at the cellular level are far less robust than simpler organisms like archaea or other extremophiles. Beyond that on the molecular scale we are primarily composed of proteins in solution. At the atomic scale it seems the elemental matter comprising those proteins itself lives inside a superfluid Higgs field. Even very dense, high-energy elements like uranium seem barely here at all, when you look at the structure carefully it is bound together by the energy generated by the complexity of the structure itself.\par
\par
Unpacking the reasons why atoms are held so apart so from each other in more complex structures like the molecules comprising elemental matter lies in studying the strong nuclear binding force and its interactions with assisting forces. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brian_Cox_(physicist)"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Brian\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brian_Cox_(physicist)"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brian_Cox_(physicist)"\cf3\ul\v0 Cox}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  has made a valiant effort to explain much of scientific understanding on broadcast television, including current best-case explanations of this mystery, by using the entire {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wonders_of_the_Universe"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Wonders\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wonders_of_the_Universe"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wonders_of_the_Universe"\cf3\ul\v0 of\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wonders_of_the_Universe"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wonders_of_the_Universe"\cf3\ul\v0 the\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wonders_of_the_Universe"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wonders_of_the_Universe"\cf3\ul\v0 Universe}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  as his example. Of course, the explanations for atoms lie A better pathway to understanding the actual explanation can be found in the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lie_group"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Exceptional\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lie_group"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lie_group"\cf3\ul\v0 Lie\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lie_group"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lie_group"\cf3\ul\v0 Group}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  of mathematical shapes. These structures were initially high-energy particle physics can currently be found by (presumably) learning to surf and hanging out with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Garret_Lisi"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Garrett\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Garret_Lisi"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Garret_Lisi"\cf3\ul\v0 Lisi}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  and talking about the structures found in coral. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Margaret\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK ""\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK ""\cf3\ul\v0 Wurtheim}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  intrinsically understands how to create these structures from her highly collaborative artistic work crocheting a coral reef, performed through her Institute For Figuring. Perhaps he is scared of being gashed or hitting his head on the stuff, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cory_doctorow"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Cory\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cory_doctorow"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cory_doctorow"\cf3\ul\v0 Doctorow}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Brin"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul David\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Brin"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Brin"\cf3\ul\v0 Brin}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  are certainly both scared as hell of uplifted coral reefs. \par
\par
There exists science fiction where farms of lobsters can be easily uplifted to intelligence which communicates with people using Internet translation services. Nobody except truly sick people want to eat sentient lobsters, so one of the first things the uplifted colony asks for is to travel via high-power transmission to another galaxy. Where they wish to go is to another galaxy in which exists a known advanced civilisation moving from Kardashev Type II to Type III. This civilisation is consuming the mass of many solar systems in its galaxy in order to build {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dyson_sphere"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Dyson\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dyson_sphere"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dyson_sphere"\cf3\ul\v0 Spheres}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  around the stars. Why? To collect enough energy to process their ever more complex thoughts. To what purpose? To facilitate better communication, resulting in the faster progression of their theory of mind and theory of everything. Language defines thought, and better communication is the most efficient pathway to better thinking. Communication is key.\par
\par
If we surmise that civilisations at Kardashev Type III ever existed at all, we must further surmise that we see no evidence of their prior existence for some reason. Rather than declaring \ldblquote the absence of evidence is no evidence of absence\rdblquote , more robust hypothesis declare that even Kardashev Level II civilisations are simply too advanced to wish to leave any evidence of their existence or even communicate with us at all. We do not talk to the amoeba on the end of our spoon before we clean the spoon for our purposes. So, how can our civilisation even \ul qualify\ulnone  as being interesting enough to even be allowed any opportunity to attempt communication with a Kardashev Type III civilisation; advanced enough to sublime from the universe leaving no trace?\par
\par
The only way is to do exactly the same thing. To \ul begin with\ulnone . Presumably, this will be such a immense undertaking we will invent and develop new ideas about interesting stuff to do afterwards along the way. But just as participating with this document is a plea for attention to its content from all who can understand, a sublimation effort (which is eventually necessary for our species, even if just to reduce its environmental footprint) is more akin to initial hopes about what such an effort means, rather than what it becomes. The good news is that the more inherently interesting anything is, the more robust, reliant, and fun it is.\par
\pard\sl276\slmult1\par
\pard\fi720\sl276\slmult1 Soon what is happening to the internet will near a point of culmination. This intrigues futurists like {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_Kurzweil"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Ray\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_Kurzweil"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_Kurzweil"\cf3\ul\v0 Kurtzweil}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  so much he {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Singularity_Is_Near"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul wrote\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Singularity_Is_Near"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Singularity_Is_Near"\cf3\ul\v0 a\cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Singularity_Is_Near"\cf3\ul\v0  \cf1\ulnone\v HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Singularity_Is_Near"\cf3\ul\v0 book}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  about it. We have long imagined the point when the internet, our best attempt at synthetic life, begins doing things on its own. We all enjoy the fruits of early attempts to do this using search engines, and we will know when these engines are closing in on intelligence when they begin providing us with information before we are aware we require it of them. This point is just off the horizon. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://google.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul Google}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  have achieved amazing success increasing the accuracy of their search engine using their {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PageRank"}}{\fldrslt{\cf3\ul PageRank}}}\cf1\ulnone\f0\fs22  system, which relies on useful statistics tracking techniques which can extrapolate many things including human traffic flocking, based on counting the number of hyperlinks any document enjoys to any other. By trying to accurately gauge everyone\rquote s interest in any particular document by counting hyperlinks, then storing that array of data in a parallel structure to one