\pard\fi720\sl276\slmult1\b0\fs22 A worthy idea for creating a specification for a new system is to write a naive version first before collecting any preconceptions of how to design the system. Then look at similar systems currently in existence and intelligently rewrite the design. This way, any unique ideas arrived at in the conceptual phase of the design process will be included in the draft of the specification, rather than omitted unnecessarily. This approach can be likened to pruning a fruit tree; in order to be healthily balanced the tree must be allowed to grow unhindered before unproductive branches are removed.\par
