In the world of mathematics, in any network of individual nodes, co-operation eventually always trumps competition. This gives rise to the concept of co-operative reciprocity trumping competitive reciprocity. In the biological world, this applies from lifeforms as simple as single-celled organisms upwards through the hierarchy of evolution. If a colony of Archean bacteria eat all substances \ul except\ulnone  each other, they will be more successful than a colony of Archean bacteria that eat all substances \ul including\ulnone  each other. In the world of economics, if networks are competitive, then \ldblquote You scratch my back, I kick you in the groin and take your back-scratcher.\rdblquote  applies. If the network is co-operative this becomes \ldblquote You scratch my back, I scratch yours. Then, with our itches resolved, we make three back-scratchers and scratch more itches.\rdblquote  Clearly, co-operative strategies of reciprocity are simply a more successful than competitive ones, especially in the long-term. While there remains a place for competition, it is being forced to the edges of the co-operative networks of society, meaning that border areas of highly co-operative economic development are encroaching slowly, expanding their influence into more competitive lesser developed areas. Conflict still occurs, but has little effect deep inside the co-operative highly-developed economic zones, which are characterised by systems of open, transparent, verifiable, and accountable government.\par
\pard\sl276\slmult1\par
\pard\fi720\sl276\slmult1 In the world of human behaviour, this concept of co-operative reciprocity was enshrined 2,000 years ago with what we know today as the \ldblquote Golden Rule\rdblquote  when someone (who could have been Jesus) said \ldblquote The meek shall inherit the earth.\rdblquote  Although they may not have known it (it is unclear whether it was understood at the level of mathematical proof at the time) due to the correctness of this principle, they were almost entirely correct. The Golden Rule distills this concept to something children can understand, which is the best point in the lives of future adults to start teaching them something so profoundly profitable to society, especially as economic development continues to occur and population pressure keeps building in a seemingly endless feedback loop.\par
